				\begin{document}$$y=A\exp \left[-\frac{{\left(x-\mu \right)}^{2}}{{2\sigma }^{2}}\right]+B$$\end{document}y=Aexp−x−μ22σ2+B, determining depth resolution by the full width at 80% of the maximum (FW80M, d = 1.33σ), following the method in prior work16. As shown in Fig. 2j, with a large illumination dose and a maximum tilt of 4°, the depth resolution improves by a factor of 2 to 3, achieving nearly atomic resolution (~0.45 nm). At lower doses, with comparable tilt angles, the improvement is even more pronounced, reaching around 0.62 nm—approximately 4 times better than MEP (2.33 nm). This improvement arises because electrons in the bright-field disk contribute significantly to the 4D-STEM dataset, while electrons in the dark-field regions remain below the Poisson noise level at low doses. TCMEP incorporates higher-angle information into the bright-field disk through specimen tilts, thereby significantly improving dose efficiency in depth sectioning.
